1281aea7-169d-4b6f-8c8b-a9ffd75ad3aa.text:
=== unplugged extra backups ===
#backup
#recovery
#sysadmin
#programmingtips

files can get mysteriously corrupted, and autosynced backups (including on rsync.net) will not save you if the source is what gets corrupted and replicated.

(-) The only way to keep them safe is to make a copy to a non-synced, maybe unplugged, destination. In other words, a manual "snapshot". This rescued some corrupted tomato/ world cup videos


(-) (even DVD-R but those are too much trouble to write to)

(-) Short of that, keeping some trash/ contents around may save your life. This is why you don't delete trash unless is choking your system (small numerous files) or huge files and you're running out of disk space. Avoid deleting trashed original content like camcorder videos. 

(-) Also, online uploads like to youtube are the only other saviour. Or sharing them with a backup buddy (like a disk at a relative's house)


2022-12-07

#sysadmin
#programmingtips

cache_ drives are an alternative to unionfs in that you overcome the mismatch between scalability layout and ease of access layout.

implication: don't bother with unionfs. It's too difficult to configure for write, and to maintain working mounts. cache_ drives have some disadvantages (organizing the master) but any time there is scalability there will be tradeoffs
